"

Enables or disables the ViPER app's sound effects, which enhance audio quality. Among these effects is the Master limiter, used to prevent distortion caused by very high volumes. It helps keep the audio clear by automatically adjusting volume peaks.


Output gain

This setting adjusts the main output volume of your device. Increasing the output gain makes the sound louder, but it is important to do this carefully to avoid distortion. Adjust the gain to achieve the desired volume and provide a more immersive audio experience.


Output pan

This function adjusts the output gain ratio between the left and right channels. The channel balance allows you to customize the sound distribution, ensuring a personalized audio experience, especially useful for users who use headphones or stereo sound systems.


Threshold limit

The threshold limit defines the maximum amplitude that the waveform can reach, acting as a limiter. The value of 0 dB represents the maximum volume without distortion. Adjusting this limit to lower values results in more aggressive compression of audio frequencies, useful for avoiding unwanted volume peaks and maintaining balanced sound quality.

"

Once an impulse response has been loaded, music will show the same characteristics as the loaded sample.


Crosschannel

Upmixes stereo to quad-channel, like this:

Channel 1: Left channel

Channel 2: x% of right channel

Channel 3: x% of left channel

Channel 4: Right channel

(x = crosschannel value)


This parameter has no effect when using quad-channel impulse responses

"

This feature allows users to load VDC headphone correction files. These files are specific to each headphone model and are used to adjust the frequency response of the audio being played. The goal is to neutralize the headphone's frequency response, ensuring that bass, midrange, and treble are reproduced in a balanced manner without excessive emphasis on any particular range. This results in a sound that is more faithful and similar to reference headphones, which are designed to provide a neutral and accurate sound reproduction.


VDC correction files are based on parametric equalization filters. These filters allow for very precise frequency response adjustments by altering different frequency bands according to the specific needs of the headphone. In addition to frequency response correction, DDC files can also be used for non-corrective adjustments, such as modifying sound characteristics to suit personal preferences or specific environments.

"

"

This feature enhances the quality of your music, making it sound as if it has \"lossless\" quality, particularly improving high frequencies. This is useful for recovering fine details in music that may be lost in compressed audio files (lossy), such as MP3 or AAC.


The system calculates the audio spectrum frequencies that were lost due to compression and attempts to reconstruct them. By enabling this feature, the audio spectrum will be rebuilt to recover high frequencies in the range of 16 kHz to 22 kHz that may have been reduced or eliminated by compression. This technique is similar to what is offered by Sony's DSEE (Digital Sound Enhancement Engine), which also aims to improve the quality of compressed audio.

"

"

The equalizer is a 10-band linear FIR (Finite Impulse Response) filter with an order of 511. This means that the equalizer has 10 adjustable frequency bands, each with precise response, thanks to the use of a high-order FIR filter.


This equalizer allows you to adjust the amplification and attenuation levels of each of the 10 frequency bands individually. This way, you can customize the frequency response of the audio according to your preferences, emphasizing or reducing specific frequency ranges to achieve the desired sound quality.

"

"

This feature creates surround sound effects, providing a more immersive listening experience. The sound field can be configured as mono or stereo, depending on your preferences and the type of audio.


Surround strength

This setting defines the intensity of the surround sound effects. The higher the intensity, the more pronounced the stereo effect will be, making the sound seem to come from the left and right sides. This creates a sense of spatiality and depth in the audio.


Mid image strength

This setting adjusts the clarity of the central vocalization. With a higher intensity, the central sound, such as the main voice in a song or movie, will be clearer and more prominent. With a lower intensity, the central sound will have a more ethereal and diffuse quality.

"

"

Also known as the precedence effect or Haas effect, this phenomenon was first described in 1949. According to the discovered law, when a sound is followed by another with a delay of approximately 40 ms or less (below the echo threshold perceived by the human ear), both sounds are perceived as a single sound.


This effect is related to how we determine the spatial location of sound. When two noises are presented with a very short delay between them, the brain perceives them as a single sound source. The spatial location is determined based on the first dominant sound that is heard, regardless of the position of the second sound.


Delay

This setting defines the delay between the left and right channels. The greater the delay, the wider the spatial effect of the sound, creating a sense of greater depth and separation between the left and right channels.

"

"

Reverberation is a sound phenomenon that occurs when sound reflects off surfaces in an environment, creating multiple repetitions that reach the ear at slightly different times, giving the impression that the sound persists for a certain period after the original sound source has stopped. In sound engineering, reverb simulation is used to replicate the acoustic sensation of different environments, such as auditoriums, living rooms, bathrooms, among others.


Room size

This parameter adjusts the perception of the virtual environment's volume. The larger the value, the longer the reverb time, creating the sensation of a larger space, such as a large auditorium or cathedral.


Sound field

Defines the width of the room in meters, influencing the perception of spatiality. The larger the value, the more immersive the sound experience, simulating an environment where the sound seems to come from different directions.


Damping factor

Controls sound absorption, simulating the humidity of the air in the environment. A higher value means that the sound is more absorbed, resulting in fewer echoes and shorter reverb.


Wet signal

Adjusts the volume of the sound processed with reverb effects. A higher wet signal intensifies the sense of space, while a lower value preserves the clarity of the original sound.


Dry signal

Regulates the volume of the original sound without reverb effects. A higher dry signal maintains the clarity and definition of the sound source.

For low-humidity environments, such as living rooms or auditoriums, use a low damping factor and adjust the room size and sound field as needed. For high-humidity environments, such as bathrooms, increase the damping factor to simulate greater echo absorption.

"

Mainly used to dynamically control, amplify or attenuate the audio volume.


Gain Ratio

Gain Ratio is the speed of amplification or attenuation, the stronger, the faster the speed and the higher the final volume. The weaker, the slower the speed, the closer to the original volume.


Max Gain

When the volume is too low, use this parameter to uplevel the sound, there may be very large magnification. The higher the value, the louder the volume. But too large will also amplify the noise within the song.


Max Output

This value defines the maximum volume of the Playback AGC sound in dB, the greater the value the greater the volume; 0 dB is the maximum.

"

This feature manipulates the dynamic range of sound, meaning it adjusts the amplitude of bass, treble, and overall audio limiting. This helps to balance and control the different sound frequencies, ensuring a more appropriate and consistent playback.


Device type

Defines the type of headphones connected to the audio input. If you cannot properly adjust the bass tone for your specific device, select \"Device default definition\" to get a default setting that should work for most headphones.


Dynamic bass strength

Defines the intensity of dynamic bass. The higher the set intensity, the stronger and more pronounced the bass will be. This allows you to adjust the depth and impact of bass sounds in the audio.

"

"

ViPER Bass replaces the XHiFi Audio Reconstruction functionality, focusing on enhancing bass at lower frequencies. This technology is designed to improve the depth and presence of bass in audio.


Bass mode

Defines the bass processing mode. Available options include:


Natural bass

Similar to the Lo Contour in ViPER XHiFi, it offers a more subtle and natural bass enhancement.


Pure bass+

Provides cleaner and more defined bass without distortion.


Subwoofer

Offers deeper and more powerful bass, simulating the presence of a physical subwoofer.


Bass frequency

Defines the cutoff frequency for bass in ViPER Bass. Adjust this setting to determine the point at which bass is enhanced or attenuated.


Bass gain

Defines the volume of the bass boost provided by ViPER Bass. Adjust this setting to increase or decrease the intensity of the bass in your audio playback.

"

"

ViPER Clarity replaces the XHiFi Audio Reconstruction functionality, offering an enhancement in audio clarity. This technology aims to improve the definition and sharpness of high frequencies and vocals in the sound.


Clarity mode

Defines the clarity mode. Available options include:


Natural

Provides an increase in vocals and treble, offering a more faithful and clear reproduction.


OZone+

Offers clean and detailed clarity, highlighting audio nuances without adding distortion.


XHiFi

Similar to the Hi Clarity in ViPER's V4A XHiFi, it provides an increase in overall audio clarity, focusing on detail definition.


Clarity gain

Defines the volume of the clarity effect provided by ViPER Clarity. Adjust this setting to increase or decrease the intensity of clarity in your audio.

"

"

This option is designed to protect the auditory system by helping to prevent damage caused by high volume levels and prolonged audio exposure.


Binaural level

Defines the strength of binaural protection. Adjust this setting to control the level of protection provided to the ears, reducing the potential impact of loud sounds and improving auditory safety.

"

"

This option defines whether the tube simulator effect is enabled. The tube simulator uses a simplified mathematical simulation to emulate the sound effect of a tube amplifier, known for its distinctive character.


When enabled, the tube simulator will significantly reduce odd-order harmonic distortions at high frequencies, which are generally associated with a rougher and less pleasant sound. In contrast, it will increase even-order harmonic distortions, which are often perceived as smoother and more pleasant, resulting in a warmer and more musical sound.

"

"

This option defines whether a field-effect transistor (FET) amplifier effect is enabled.


AnalogX

Uses a simplified mathematical simulation to emulate the behavior of a field-effect transistor. This effect is designed to replicate the typical sound characteristics of FET amplifiers, providing a sound that may include a slight harmonic distortion and a distinct tonal quality.

"

"

Optimizes the audio quality of the smartphone's internal speaker.


This setting equalizes the internal speaker to provide a more neutral and balanced sound. It adjusts the frequencies to improve clarity and fidelity, reducing distortions and enhancing the overall quality of sound reproduction.

"

The field-effect transistor (FET) is a type of transistor which uses an electric field to control the flow of current. FETs are devices with three terminals: source, gate, and drain. FETs control the flow of current by the application of a voltage to the gate, which in turn alters the conductivity between the drain and source.

ViPER is capable of simulating this system.


Threshold

The threshold control sets the level at which the compression effect is engaged. Only when a level passes above the threshold will it be compressed. If the threshold level is set at say -10 dB, only signal peaks that extend above that level will be compressed. The rest of the time, no compression will be taking place.


Ratio

Compression ratio specifies the amount of attenuation to be applied to the signal.


Knee

The “knee” refers to how the compressor transitions between the non-compressed and compressed states of an audio signal running through it.


Attack

This refers to the time it takes for the signal to become fully compressed after exceeding the threshold level.


Release

This is literally the opposite of attack time. More specifically, it is the time it takes for the signal to go from the compressed — or attenuated — state back to the original non-compressed signal. Release times will be considerably longer than attack times.


Gain

Raise the volume of the result


Crest

Distance between the highest and electrically average audio


Adapt

Time to average


Clipping prevention

To prevent static-like artifacts when the volume is too high to work with
